{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949021801/0958.xml":{"full_text":"Forecast And\nWeather Report\nNome and Vicinity\nCompiled by the U. S. Dept, ot\nCommerce, Weather Bureau.\nFriday, February 18, 1949\nForecast Nome: Mostly cloudy\nand warmer tonight and Satur\nday. Intermitten light snow Sat\nurday. Fresh to strong east wind:\nWarming temperatures to 20 above\nSaturday.\nNome data last 24 hours as of\n7:00 a.m. today:\nPrecipitation none. <Total this\nmonth 0.97 inch.)\nTemperatures: highest 9. lowest\n0.\nMaximum wind 26 miles an\nhour from the east.\nSunrise at 7:47 a.m., sunset at\n4:43 p.m.\nComparative data: Tempera\ntures one year ago today: highest\n2, lowest \u201422.\nExtreme temperatures on this\ndate since 1907: highest 39 in\n1934, lowest \u201434 in 1932.\nData for other selected stations\nas of 7:00 a.m. today:\nStation Temp. Weather\nBarrow \u201423 Cloudy\nPoint Hope \u201416 Clear\nKotzebue \u20146 Partly Cloudy\nShishmaref \u201411 Cloudy\nWales \u201417 Cloudy\nGambell 10 Cloudy\nNome 2 Cloudy\nUnalakleet \u20144 Cloudy\nBethel \u20146 Cloudy\nMcGrath \u201435 Partly Cloudy\nAnchorage \u20148 Partly Cloudy\nFairbanks \u201432 Partly Cloudy\nWhitehorse \u201436 Clear\nEdmonton \u201419 Cloudy\nJuneau 0 Clear\nKetchikan 13 Clear\nSeattle 37 Cloudy1\nSan Francisco 4 Cloudy\nUNION SEEKS DAMAGES\nFROM PACKERS ASSN.\nSEATTLE, </P)\u2014A legal action\nseeking $451,581 damages p om the\nAlaska Packers association was\nfiled in superior court Wednesday\nby the cannery workers and farm\nlaborers\u2019 union, Local 7, and Er\nnesto Mangoaang, its business\nagent.\n\u2666The complaint said the packers\nsalmon cannery operators, paid 70\nemployees part of their wages\nwhen they returned from Larsen\nBay, Alaska, August 1946, and\nmost of the balance due them in\nFebruary, 1948.\nThe union asks that the men be\npaid wages and subsistence for the\ninterval between payments.\nAIRLINES\nPAN AMERICAN AIRWAYS\nArriving Thursday with Pan\nAmerican Airways were Mr. and\nMrs. Harry Gottschalk, Wallen\nChapman, Jimmy Otiyohek, Frank\nDegnan and infant June Bahr,\nFloyd Olaneo.\nDeparting were Antonio Polet,\nW. C. Richey, Mr. and Mrs. Axel\nEdman, Major Terry, Mr. and\nMrs. H. Harper and Floyd Olaneo.\nWIEN ALASKA AIRLINES\n1 Wednesday a flight was made\nfrom Kotzebue bringing in Ed\nMears, Herb Pickering, Major R.\nTerry, and Mrs. Roy Seradlook\nwas taken from Wales to Kotze\nbue.\nYesterday the Golovin mail run\nwas made.\nYesterday Mrs. Peterson was a\npassenger to Teller and Mrs. Ver-:\nnon Konukpeok was brought in to\nNome.\nThe basketball team was taken\nto Anchorage for the Fur Rendez\nvous.\nI\nALASKA AIRLINES\nPassengers departing for Una\nlakleet today were Mr. and Mrs.\nFrank Degnan, and An drew\nBango.\nAT THE WALLACE HOTEL\nPreston Stocum, Moses Point.\n\nAT THE POLARIS HOTEL\nHerb Pickering, E. L. Neares,\nFairbanks. Marie Stafford, Ta\ncoma.\nHAWAIIAN GOVERNOR GIVEN\nNEW 50-STAR U. S. FLAG\nHONOLULU, (lP)\u2014A flag with\n50 stars, the gift of the Anchor\nage, Alaska, central labor council,1\nwas preesnted to Gov. Ingram\nStainback at the opening of the\n25th territorial legislature Wed\nnesday.\nThe flag symbolizes the hopes\nof Hawaii and Alaska to become\nstates of the Union. The flag has\nsix rows of seven stars and a row\nin the center with eight stars.\nWiLfred C. Tsukisama, Hawaii\n\u2022born Japanese, was elected presi\ndent of the Senate and Hiram L.\nFong, Hawaii-born Chinese, was\nnamed speaker of the House.\nTsukisama is the first Japanese\never elected as a presiding officer\nof the Hawaiian legislature.\nHome is a place where some\nmen go to raise cain because\nsomething went wrong at the of\nfice.\nmamm\nBULLETINS\nt\n(Contined from Page One)\ndistrict in which it is collected.\nJUNEAU. (TP) The Se n a t e\npassed unanimously memorials to\nCongress or federal officials; to\ni put an Alaskan on the internation\nal fisheries commission; for a road\nacross Prince Wales Island; to im\nprove the transportation in the\nUnalakleet Island area by cutting\na channel through Unalakleet bar\nor building a ninety-mile Unala\nkleet-Kaltag link to avoid the six\n[hundred mile trip up the Yukon\nto Kaltag. Jones Memorial asked\nthe study of one or both of Unala\nklet projects.\nThe Senate killed nine to five\nthis afternoon the proposed doub\nling of motor fuels tax. The only\nvotes for it were by Barr of Fair\nbanks, who introduced it and all\nthe Senators from the Third Divi\nsion\u2014Huntley, McCutcheon, Riv\ners and Engebreth.\nJUNEAU, (/P) Alaska\u2019s first\ngeneral property tax was assured\nthis afternoon when the House\nconcurred Senate amendments a\nfew hours after Senate passage.\nThe House vote to concur was\n18 to 6. Governor Gruening smil-\ning broadly and shaking legisla-!\ntors\u2019 hands, said he would sign the\nbill as soon as it reaches his desk\ntomorrow or Monday.\nVotes against concurring were:\nGundersen, Hope, Jensen, Frank\nO. Johnson, Frank L. Johnson and j\nRydeen.\n\nAlthough Milan, Italy, w a s j\nfounded in ancient times, its relics j\nof antiquity are few because the\ncity was burned several times.\nNOTICE\nI\nChaplain Darling will be the\nguest speaker at the Nazarene\nChurch Sunday evening.\nATTENTION\nArctic Native Brotherhood\nmembers. Important meeting to be\nheld at the Club House. Friday at\n7:30 p.m.. Feb. 18.\nSam Mogg, Secy.\nNOTICE\n^ll-^\nThe Poll Book for the registra\ntion of voters for the forthcoming\nMunicipal and School-board elec\ntion will be open Wednesday. Feb.\n16th. 1949. EHection takes place\nApril 5. 1949.\nCARRIE M. McLAIN.\nCity Clerk.\nPublish Feb. 14, 16, 18, 1949.\nClassified Ads\n\u2014...x _____I\nREAL SILK Hosiery Mills wiil\nemploy local -woman in Nome. Our\nline is very complete and priced\nright. Well known here. Write L.\nE. Bolton, Box 115, Anchorage,\ngiving local references only, etc.\n20-3tc\nAIRPLANES\u2014Send for free list.\nAll makes and models. World's\nlargest s*ock and lowest prices!\nIt\u2019s easy to buy from us\u2014we do\neverything for you except pay\nfor the airplane. Vest Ai^raft\nCo., 46TOO Dahlia, Denver, Colo.\n126-tfc\nTANNING\u2014Send us your skins\nand furs to be tanned. Quick, ef\nficient, reliable. Valcauda Fur\nCo., National Bldg., Seattle.\nWash. 103-tf\nFOUND\u2014Billfold of Josie Nanoo\nruk. Call at Nugget. 19-tf\nTruman Optimistic\nFor Continued\nU. S. Prosperity\n(By Francis E. Le May)\nWASHINGTON, (/P\u00bb\u2014President\nTruman\u2019s confident forecast of\ncontinued prosperity brought this\nreaction today from his Capitol\nHill critics: the best way to help\nthe nation\u2019s business is to leave it\nalone.\nThe President also renewed his\nrequest yesterday for a four bil\nlion dollar tax boost\u2014a proposal\nvvhich appeared to be picking up\nsupport from Democrats, but only\nif necessary to keep the treasury\nout of the red. There is a lot of\nopposition, however.\nMr. Truman told his Thursday\nnews conference current price\ndrops are only the leveling-off\nthat everybody has been hoping\nfor, and he spoke confidently of\nthe business outlook. He said the\nbusiness situation is nothing to be\nalarmed about.\nSome critics agreed that the\nlevelling off is healthy. But they\nsaid the President\u2019s economic con\ntrol program, if approved by Con\ngress, might turn a healthy re\ncession into a depression.\nWhile Mr. Truman took the\neconomic temperature, there were\nthese other developments:\n1. Buying interest in the New\nYork stock market 'sharpened yes-\nterday and the market moved\nahead for the best overall advance 1\nin six weeks.\n2. At Cleveland, the Chesapeake\nOhio Railroad announced tem\nporary layoffs for more than 4,000\nemployees in four areas. A spokes\nman blamed declining passenger\nbusiness and slower movement of\ncoal due to a mild winter.\n3. The Baltimore Ohio Rail\nroad ordered a five-day furlough\nlate this month for 2,521 of its\nshop employees.\n4. A majority of the 17 private\nFire Does Much\nDamage At Hawk\nInlet Cannery\nj JUNEAU, Fire of undetermined\norigin destroyed the commissary\nand bunkhouse of the large P. E.\nHarris Co., cannery at Hawk In\nlet, 15 miles southwest of here on\nAdmiralty Island, late Wednes\nday.\nThe plant itself, valued at\n$1,500,000 to $2,000,000, was still\nun'ouched, latest reports said. The\nburned buildings were south of\nthe main cannery installations\nand a still north wind was blow\ning away from the cannery.\nW. C. Arnold, manager of the\nAlaska Canned Salmon Industry,\nInc., said the fire was still burn\ning. He said the main buildings\nwere dispersed so well there was\na good chance they would be spar\ned. No water was available for\nfire-fighting because of a freeze\nup.\nThe plant is one of the largest\nin Southeastern Alaska. First re\nports said only a caretaker and\nhis wife were stationed there.\nThe Bermudas were discovered\nby Juan de Bermudez in 1510.\nindustry economists attending a\nCapitol Hill conference spoke out\nagainst the administration\u2019s re\nquest for higher taxes and wage\nprice allocation controls.\nThe House yesterday voted to\nlet the President keep part of the\npower he now has. A bill extend\ning export controls for 28 months\nwas passed and sent to the Sen\nate, which has approved a similar\nmeasure with slight differences.\nMr. Truman told his news con\nference, in answer to a question,\nthat he has no plan now to modify\ninstallment buying controls. Rep.\nPatman (D.-Tex.\u2019 has argued the\ncontrols are hurting business.\nMINERS MERCHANTS\nBANK OF ALASKA\nNOME ALASKA\nNORTHERN LIGHT POWER CO.\nELECTRICAL APPLIANCES\nG-E Dial-the-fabric Iron G-E Steam Iron\nG-E Automatic Roaster G-E Hotplate\nG-E Washing Machine G-E Sun Lamp\nG-E Electric Clock G-E Mazda Lamps\nWiring Materials\nARCTIC OIL DELIVERY\nPhene\u2014Shep: Bleck Residence: Mein 52\nN j\nWE CHECK YOUR TANK REGULARLY\n\nBEN young t\nUNTIL FURTHER NOTICE\nTHE NOME LIQUOR STORE\nWILL REMAIN OPEN\nFOR COLLECTION OF ACCOUNTS ONLY","height":"27396","width":"20408"}}
